íŸ@05d68d74be6724aaa6425adb1ec63c229bf5e82adb05f7b3e965b454741df73e⁄«Title: title: open
Path: Examples
Content:
Open a file, with structure (based on file extension or SQLite database header).
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> open myfile.json


```
Open a file, as raw bytes.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> open myfile.json --raw


```
Open a file, using the input to get filename.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> 'myfile.txt' | open


```
Open a file, and decode it by the specified encoding.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> open myfile.txt --raw | decode utf-8


```
Create a custom 
``from``
 parser to open newline-delimited JSON files with 
``open``
.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> def "from ndjson" [] { from json -o }; open myfile.ndjson


```
Show the extensions for which the 
``open``
 command will automatically parse.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> scope commands
    | where name starts-with "from "
    | insert extension { get name | str replace -r "^from " "" | $"*.($in)" }
    | select extension name
    | rename extension command



```
íŸ@9f47ff7132ef1eb98e61250b08bbe3e8a10b0263b374163e4952a0dd5116b0a2ŸÝTitle: title: open
Path: Notes
Content:
Support to automatically parse files with an extension 
``.xyz``
 can be provided by a 
``from xyz``
 command in scope.
